title Quin's dispatch loop, pseudocoded against the four voices' real APIs
prompt Keaton asked what the most abstract unimplemented design in the tree is, and asked for pseudocode design docs implementing it in terms of the system so far, to read during a phone call before switching to the Framework session.
think surveyed candidates before picking one: Ojjo (benchmarking), Rhyz (identity revival, 72-file migration deferred), the Glow supplement's own remaining surfaces (runes, auras, jet-state, mold nesting), and Quin (the inference Q-vane). Chose Quin specifically because it is named, in its own settled entry, as kernel-quiet and built only "when Glow can host an agent" -- the most explicitly gated-open, most abstract-by-design unbuilt surface in the tree, and because the four voices it would unify (Lattice, Lantern, Anvil, Scribble) are all already built and green, giving real APIs to ground pseudocode in rather than inventing signatures from nothing.
think checked the designed-not-yet-built gate (parity witness scanning context/specs/*.md for that exact status phrase, capped at one spec in flight) before writing anything -- count was 0, plenty of room, and placed this doc in active-designing/ rather than context/specs/ regardless, since it is an unbound design exploration rather than a functional spec entering that specific gate's flight.
think read all four voices' real _core.rye files directly rather than working from memory or the prior Quin research doc's own summary -- pulled exact struct fields and function signatures (Lattice's Matrix/matmul, Lantern's Request/Response/complete_allowed, Anvil's Catalog/CorpusQuery/query_corpus, Scribble's Block/parse_markdown/extract_rye_snippets) so the proposed QuinTurn/run_turn pseudocode composes real, current APIs rather than plausible-sounding invented ones.
think noticed and named a real pattern across all four voices worth stating once rather than assuming: every function takes pre-sized output storage and a request/query struct, returns a bounded count or a named error, never allocates or grows mid-call. Held Quin's own proposed dispatch loop to the same standard rather than let a composing layer quietly reintroduce unboundedness the four voices themselves already refuse.
think deliberately did not force Lattice into the composed turn just to use all four voices in one pass -- named plainly that none of the four voices' current real APIs produce anything Lattice's tensor ops could consume (Anvil's query is structural, not semantic/embedded), and pointed at the honest future rung (embeddings in the catalog, scored by Lattice) where Lattice would actually enter, rather than manufacturing a call that would not really do anything.
think named the halting bound explicitly as its own section, since an inference dispatch loop is exactly the shape of code that quietly grows an open retry-while-loop over time -- tied this to TAME's own bounded-execution discipline applying to control flow, not only buffer sizes, and named what a future retry rung would need (an explicit max_retries_per_turn) rather than leaving it implicit.
think connected the design to the sandbox composition already confirmed in the prior Quin research (Quin x Puddle x Neth) by naming that QuinTurn's own plain, serializable shape is exactly what makes it seedable and byte-for-byte replayable under Neth's own deterministic-harness discipline -- ties this new design to the tree's existing decisions rather than floating free of them.
obs this is a genuinely honest "abstract and unimplemented" pick: everything the design sits on already exists and is green (four real modules), while the design itself is deliberately, explicitly zero lines, gated on a real precondition (Lantern moving past fixture-served completion) that has not yet arrived -- named that gate plainly rather than implying the pseudocode alone unblocks anything.
